e-Aquitaine, Frankrijk","Ségur-le-Château, Corrèze, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Ségur-le-Château, Corrèze, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1165–":"1165–Deceased","1160–Male":"1160–Deceased","1165–Female":"1165–Deceased","1155–1230":"1155–1230","1179–1243":"1179–1243","1145–Male":"1145–Deceased","1145–Female":"1145–Deceased","1179":"1179","1145":"1145","1243":"1243","1155":"1155","1165":"1165","1230":"1230","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","Rochechouart, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Rochechouart, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France","Ségur-le-Château, Corrèze, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Ségur-le-Château, Corrèze, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Pérusse","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Colette, Laurette, Marcel, Roch.","French (<b>Pérusse</b>): habitational name from (La) Pérusse or Perrusse, names of several places in various parts of France."],"variants":[]},{"name":"des","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Indian: variant of   Deo  . In Maharashtra, Konkanastha Brahmins have a clan called Dev."],"variants":[{"name":"Deo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ravindra, Sohini, Vivek, Ajay, Alok, Anil, Annapurna, Daya, Ganga, Goutam, Harnek, Indra.","Indian (northern states): from Sanskrit <i>deva</i> ‘deity, lord’. This was a title used by ruling families in northern India. There is a Jat tribe called Deo. In northeastern India this name is spelled and pronounced   Deb  . Elsewhere, a common variant is   Dev  .","Italian: from a short form of the personal names <i>Amadeo</i>, <i>Laudadeo</i>, or <i>Sperindeo</i>, of which only the first now remains in use as a personal name."]}]},{"name":"Cars","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Greek: variant of   Karas  . Compare   Carras  .","American shortened and altered form of Greek <b>Kyriakos</b>: from the personal name <i>Kyriakos</i> (see   Kyriacou  ).","Romanian: nickname from <i>caras</i> ‘crucian carp’ (Carassius vulgaris), a word of Slavic origin (see   Karas  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Karas","meanings":["Polish (<b>Karaś</b>) and Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic; also <b>Karaś</b>); Ukrainian, Belorussian, Czech, Slovak, Croatian, Slovenian, and Sorbian: from Polish <i>karaś</i>, other Slavic <i>karas</i> ‘crucian carp (Carassius vulgaris)’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a carp fisher or possibly a nickname for someone thought to resemble the fish. As a Jewish name it is mainly artificial. Compare   Caras  ,   Karasch  , and   Karras  .","Hungarian: topographic name for someone living by the Karas river, a tributary of the Danube, named with Turkish <i>kara</i> ‘black’.","Americanized form of Hungarian <b>Kárász</b>, a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Lucie","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin.  See  <b>Lucy</b>   . This has now largely replaced the older French form  Luce ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lucie de Pérusse des Cars was born in 1165, in Ségur-le-Château, Corrèze, No